Here, man. You try that, bro.

10:27.458 --> 10:28.708
Ah, thanks.

10:28.708 --> 10:29.834
Then when you're done, you

10:29.834 --> 10:30.959
meet me down at the bar.

10:30.959 --> 10:31.959
We'll have some drinks.

10:31.959 --> 10:33.083
All right, then.

10:46.500 --> 10:48.209
[SIGHS]

10:48.209 --> 10:49.166
Ah...

10:51.167 --> 10:52.167
Jack: [SIGHS] Can't believe

10:52.167 --> 10:53.291
you're leaving tomorrow, man.

10:53.291 --> 10:54.583
Dawson: Tell me about it.

10:54.583 --> 10:57.167
LA is a galaxy far, far away.

10:57.167 --> 10:58.875
Yet only five hours away by
plane.

10:59.167 --> 11:00.167
Nervous?

11:00.959 --> 11:02.500
Yeah, nervous. I'm excited,

11:02.500 --> 11:06.000
I'm... I'm exhilarated, I'm
depressed.

11:06.708 --> 11:08.417
That pretty much sums it up.

11:08.417 --> 11:10.125
Are you sure you don't want to
stick around?

11:10.125 --> 11:10.875
You could be painting Mrs.

11:10.875 --> 11:11.875
Hammacott's house this summer.

11:11.875 --> 11:13.041
Ha ha. Oh, God.

11:13.041 --> 11:14.041
Do it with Joey.

11:14.041 --> 11:15.208
I'm sure she'll jump at the
chance

11:15.208 --> 11:16.583
to free herself from the
clutches

11:16.583 --> 11:18.084
of Cruella Devalentine.

11:18.458 --> 11:21.917
Yeah. Yeah, she's really gonna
miss you, Dawson.

11:21.917 --> 11:23.792
Yeah, she's got plenty on her
mind.

11:24.583 --> 11:25.875
Infiltrating the Ivy Leagues...

11:25.875 --> 11:28.333
The whole devastating break-up
thing.

11:28.333 --> 11:30.583
Come on, man. I know, that's
all true,

11:30.583 --> 11:32.208
but you and Joey saying
good-bye,

11:32.208 --> 11:34.042
that's a fairly colossal event.

11:36.458 --> 11:38.083
Why is everybody so determined
to shake me

11:38.083 --> 11:40.000
out my cozy little cocoon of
denial?

11:40.000 --> 11:42.250
Because if you don't at least
acknowledge

11:42.250 --> 11:44.375
the hugeness of this moment,

11:44.625 --> 11:47.125
you are gonna wake up in some
cold sweat

11:47.125 --> 11:48.125
in some USC dorm room one night,

11:48.125 --> 11:49.500
and you're just gonna have one
more thing

11:49.500 --> 11:51.041
to add to your list of lifelong
regrets.

11:52.875 --> 11:53.792
Could you do me a favor?

11:53.792 --> 11:54.458
Yeah, anything.

11:54.458 --> 11:56.125
Don't sit next to me at the
movies tonight, man.

11:56.125 --> 11:57.083
You're bummin' me out.

11:57.083 --> 11:58.625
Come on, man. You can't tell me

11:58.625 --> 12:00.167
you haven't at least thought
about it.

12:00.792 --> 12:01.417
What?

12:01.417 --> 12:03.042
What? The opportunity

12:03.042 --> 12:04.708
to spend the entire summer with
her.

12:07.208 --> 12:08.834
Of course I've thought about it.

12:10.083 --> 12:12.084
I've thought about it so much
it makes me mad

12:12.084 --> 12:13.041
because I don't understand why I

12:13.041 --> 12:14.208
can't stop thinking about it.

12:17.834 --> 12:19.041
[SIGHS] I fell in love with

12:19.041 --> 12:20.500
somebody else this year.

12:20.917 --> 12:21.834
Do you have any idea how

12:21.834 --> 12:22.959
significant that is for me?

12:22.959 --> 12:23.959
I mean...

12:27.625 --> 12:29.333
So why can't I stop thinking
about her?

12:30.417 --> 12:31.959
You gonna miss him?

12:32.834 --> 12:34.084
Aren't you?

12:34.417 --> 12:35.917
Yeah, but that's different.

12:36.209 --> 12:37.333
How's it different?

12:37.667 --> 12:40.125
'Cause I had all last summer

12:40.125 --> 12:41.125
to get sick of Dawson and

12:41.125 --> 12:42.417
his quirks, his foibles.

12:42.959 --> 12:44.333
All those annoying little
things that he does

12:44.333 --> 12:45.250
that make you just want to

12:45.250 --> 12:46.166
throw him into the creek.

12:46.166 --> 12:47.708
He is rather annoying, isn't he?

12:47.708 --> 12:48.792
Oh, God, yeah.

12:48.792 --> 12:50.000
I mean, the way he makes you
sit through

12:50.000 --> 12:51.583
all of the credits at the end
of a movie.

12:51.583 --> 12:54.042
Ha! Out of respect for the
filmmaker, of course.

12:54.042 --> 12:55.500
And the incessant picture-taking

12:55.500 --> 12:57.042
and crushing self-analysis.

12:57.042 --> 12:58.083
Not to mention that thing he
does

12:58.083 --> 12:59.208
where he puts you up on a
pedestal

12:59.208 --> 13:01.125
and makes you the center of his
universe. God...

13:06.000 --> 13:07.333
If you asked him to stay, he
would.

13:09.458 --> 13:11.333
What? Give up the movie-making

13:11.333 --> 13:12.875
chance of a lifetime

13:12.875 --> 13:13.917
just so he can bum around.

13:13.917 --> 13:15.209
Capeside for another summer?

13:15.209 --> 13:16.209
Ha ha ha.

13:16.458 --> 13:17.500
I don't think he'd see it

13:17.500 --> 13:18.583
as such a bad trade-off.

13:19.458 --> 13:21.625
What makes you think that I
want him to stay?

13:22.625 --> 13:24.000
You really want to know?

13:24.500 --> 13:25.166
Yeah.

13:25.166 --> 13:26.750
It's this little voice inside
my head

13:26.750 --> 13:28.250
that says "I like your hair
color."

13:28.250 --> 13:29.250
What number is that?"

13:29.792 --> 13:30.792
[CHUCKLES]

13:32.167 --> 13:33.583
You still hate me, don't you?

13:34.167 --> 13:35.084
No, I don't hate you.

13:35.084 --> 13:36.583
I mean, I don't get it, Jen.

13:37.500 --> 13:39.750
I mean, how am I supposed to
feel about this?

13:40.041 --> 13:41.167
Am I supposed to feel good

13:41.167 --> 13:42.166
knowing that I have the power

13:42.166 --> 13:43.542
to change somebody's life?

13:45.084 --> 13:46.084
I don't know. I mean, I think

13:46.084 --> 13:47.167
that we all have the power

13:47.167 --> 13:48.166
to change each other's lives.

13:49.166 --> 13:50.708
The questions is...

13:50.708 --> 13:51.917
Are you going to use it?

13:54.333 --> 13:55.834
Jen: Hi. Four, please.

13:57.125 --> 13:58.291
What were you girls talking
about?

13:59.291 --> 14:00.542
Oh, you know...

14:00.542 --> 14:01.542
Um...

14:01.834 --> 14:03.417
Hair, makeup, world peace.

14:03.417 --> 14:04.417
Usual girl stuff.

14:05.084 --> 14:06.042
There you go.

14:06.042 --> 14:07.250
- Thank you. - Thanks.

14:07.250 --> 14:08.458
Here you go.

14:10.000 --> 14:11.000
Jen: All right.

14:26.166 --> 14:28.042
Dawson: [SIGHS] So, who's
hungry?

14:29.167 --> 14:31.125
Well, I should go home and
check on Grams.

14:31.125 --> 14:32.583
I feel kind of guilty about
leaving her.

14:35.250 --> 14:37.625
But if, you know, if you guys
want to go eat,

14:37.625 --> 14:39.333
actually food... Food is good.

14:39.333 --> 14:40.333
I could eat.

14:40.792 --> 14:41.834
Actually, you know what?

14:41.834 --> 14:43.125
I haven't packed yet.

14:43.125 --> 14:44.458
I still have to do that tonight.

14:45.167 --> 14:46.125
Unless we just want to...

14:46.125 --> 14:48.000
Jen: Yeah. I mean, why don't
you guys go ahead.

14:48.000 --> 14:49.208
I'm sure you've got a lot to
talk about.

14:49.208 --> 14:50.834
And Jack and I will just walk.

14:51.458 --> 14:52.458
I could walk.

14:52.875 --> 14:54.333
Oh. Yeah, whatever.

14:54.667 --> 14:56.250
It's not like my evening will
be incomplete

14:56.250 --> 14:58.000
without greasy diner food, so...

14:58.000 --> 14:59.084
Ok.

15:02.667 --> 15:03.917
So what did we just decide?

15:04.625 --> 15:05.625
Uh, um...

15:08.250 --> 15:10.458
I guess we decided to go home.

15:11.041 --> 15:12.625
Great. Home.

15:13.042 --> 15:14.041
Uh, who's first?

15:14.959 --> 15:16.625
Well, I live next door.

15:16.625 --> 15:18.083
Yeah, my car's at her house.

15:18.750 --> 15:20.166
[CLEARS THROAT] Guess I'm first.

15:23.209 --> 15:24.917
Gale: Ok, which one do you like
better?

15:24.917 --> 15:26.291
Lily looking adorable in her

15:26.291 --> 15:27.917
bassinet with her pink bow,

15:28.041 --> 15:29.625
or Lily looking adorable in her

15:29.625 --> 15:31.083
bassinet with her yellow bow?

15:31.083 --> 15:33.166
Oh, and then of course we have
this one

15:33.166 --> 15:35.166
of her looking adorable with
Dawson. Hmm.

15:37.333 --> 15:38.959
They got the same Leery eyes,
don't they?

15:38.959 --> 15:41.209
Mm-hmm. Self-aware with hidden
depth.

15:41.209 --> 15:43.125
Same Leery cheekbones.

15:43.125 --> 15:44.167
Camera loves them.

15:44.167 --> 15:45.792
Same heartthrob smile.

15:47.083 --> 15:48.417
Which is probably hiding a

15:48.417 --> 15:50.167
stubborn streak 10 miles long.

15:50.167 --> 15:52.333
What do you say the odds are,
18 years from now,

15:52.333 --> 15:53.875
Lily might actually have the
good sense

15:53.875 --> 15:55.125
to listen to her father before

15:55.125 --> 15:56.167
she heads off to college?

15:57.166 --> 15:59.083
She might want to spend some
time with her family

15:59.083 --> 16:01.291
before facing the great unknown.

16:02.083 --> 16:03.959
Mm. It's a big step, going away.

16:03.959 --> 16:05.333
And it isn't always easy.

16:06.417 --> 16:08.333
And neither is getting left
behind.

16:08.333 --> 16:10.417
And not being needed anymore.

16:11.041 --> 16:12.167
Excuse me?

16:12.167 --> 16:13.417
That big stand you took earlier?

16:14.167 --> 16:16.209
That desperate plea for family
togetherness?

16:16.834 --> 16:19.959
Obviously the last gasp of a
dying dictatorship.

16:19.959 --> 16:21.167
Oh, funny word, dictatorship.

16:21.167 --> 16:22.041
You're blaming me.

16:22.041 --> 16:23.333
No. I'm not blaming anybody.

16:23.333 --> 16:24.583
Yes, you are. You're blaming me.

16:24.583 --> 16:28.625
No. I just think that certain
people,

16:28.625 --> 16:30.750
when they're feeling insecure
about the future,

16:30.750 --> 16:32.042
would rather pick a fight

16:32.042 --> 16:33.000
and stomp around in the front

16:33.000 --> 16:33.834
yard than face the fact

16:33.834 --> 16:36.125
that they are feeling insecure
about the future.

16:37.417 --> 16:38.333
Oh, did I happen to mention

16:38.333 --> 16:40.167
that those people are usually
men?

16:41.417 --> 16:43.750
Why would I be feeling insecure
about the future?

16:43.750 --> 16:45.458
I'm not the one whose life is
about to change.

16:46.667 --> 16:48.667
I think we may have just
discovered where our son

16:48.667 --> 16:50.209
gets his talent for denial.

17:04.040 --> 17:05.458
Well, uh, later, Joey.

17:05.834 --> 17:07.165
Hey, call me tomorrow, ok?

17:07.165 --> 17:08.165
Ok.

17:10.165 --> 17:11.458
So I guess this is it, right?

17:11.458 --> 17:13.000
Uh, yeah. Let me walk you to
the...

17:13.083 --> 17:14.083
Great.

17:21.708 --> 17:23.791
Well, I had a really nice time
tonight.

17:23.791 --> 17:24.791
Yeah. Me, too.

17:25.125 --> 17:26.333
It's comforting, you know?

17:26.333 --> 17:27.625
What's that?

17:27.625 --> 17:29.291
Well, seeing a movie that
you've seen before.

17:30.250 --> 17:32.208
Yeah. You don't have to waste
any creative energy

17:32.208 --> 17:33.917
trying to figure out how it's
gonna end.

17:35.084 --> 17:36.291
It's gonna be weird, isn't it?

17:37.042 --> 17:37.792
What?

17:37.792 --> 17:40.083
Next year. I mean, me in Boston.

17:40.083 --> 17:41.500
You in Los Angeles.

17:43.208 --> 17:44.417
Yeah.

17:47.083 --> 17:48.959
Well, you're gonna have
celebrity sightings

17:48.959 --> 17:50.083
left and right, you know.

17:50.083 --> 17:50.084
left and right, you know.
Ha ha ha. I don't think LA
really works that way.

17:50.084 --> 17:52.667
Ha ha ha. I don't think LA
really works that way.

17:52.667 --> 17:54.042
Sure it does.

17:55.083 --> 17:57.084
One day, you're gonna turn
around in line

17:57.084 --> 17:59.084
in some overpriced organic food
store,

17:59.084 --> 18:02.167
or you'll be in a movie line at
some mall,

18:02.167 --> 18:03.834
because there are tons of malls
in LA,

18:03.834 --> 18:06.166
and you will see him, Dawson.

18:07.084 --> 18:08.084
Who?

18:08.542 --> 18:09.542
Spielberg.

18:10.167 --> 18:11.125
I'm actually in more of a.

18:11.125 --> 18:12.000
Soderbergh phase right now.

18:13.167 --> 18:14.167
Regardless.

18:14.917 --> 18:16.125
What would you say to him if
you saw him?

18:16.125 --> 18:17.166
- Spielberg? - Yeah.

18:17.166 --> 18:20.166
I'd... I... I don't know.

18:20.667 --> 18:21.959
Dawson, come on.

18:22.417 --> 18:23.875
I mean, this is the guy who
shaped

18:23.875 --> 18:25.083
your entire world view.

18:25.083 --> 18:27.583
Who eased all of your childhood
traumas,

18:27.583 --> 18:30.083
and who made growing up just a
bit more bearable.

18:31.917 --> 18:32.917
Um...

18:34.875 --> 18:35.792
In that case,

18:35.792 --> 18:37.166
I guess I'd just have to...

18:38.125 --> 18:39.125
Say thank you.

18:45.291 --> 18:47.625
Doesn't quite seem like enough,
does it?

18:50.084 --> 18:51.041
No, it doesn't.

19:00.000 --> 19:02.042
So I guess see you at
Thanksgiving.

19:03.333 --> 19:04.834
Actually, uh, my parents had
talked

19:04.834 --> 19:06.125
about bringing Lily out to LA.

19:06.166 --> 19:07.125
Dawson: So...

19:07.125 --> 19:08.125
Oh. um...

19:08.917 --> 19:10.125
Well, then Christmas.

19:10.125 --> 19:11.208
Yeah, Christmas. Definitely.

19:11.583 --> 19:12.750
Definitely. Yeah.

19:19.333 --> 19:20.167
Well, good luck.

19:20.167 --> 19:21.375
Hey, you, too.

19:32.000 --> 19:33.000
See you, Dawson.

19:41.167 --> 19:42.500
[SIGHS]

19:57.417 --> 19:58.625
[MUMBLING]

20:05.209 --> 20:06.083
See you, Joey.

20:16.208 --> 20:17.917
Well, should we give it to him
now?

20:17.917 --> 20:19.042
- Now's good. - All right.

20:19.208 --> 20:21.084
- What? - Ha ha ha.

20:24.250 --> 20:25.250
You didn't?

20:26.542 --> 20:29.125
Well, we figured that you
should have one in LA.

20:29.917 --> 20:31.417
It was either that or a BMW.

20:31.417 --> 20:33.042
You guys, this... You didn't
have to do this.

20:33.042 --> 20:34.042
This is too much.

20:34.042 --> 20:35.125
Don't get too excited.

20:35.125 --> 20:36.250
We can only afford, like, what,

20:36.250 --> 20:37.917
five minutes of air time?

20:40.959 --> 20:42.333
This is great. Thank you.

20:42.333 --> 20:43.333
Jack: Sure.

20:44.708 --> 20:46.333
Ok, you guys. Get it over with.
Hug.

20:46.333 --> 20:48.167
Ha ha ha.

20:48.167 --> 20:49.500
- Come here. - All right, man.
Heh.

20:49.500 --> 20:50.500
[JACK LAUGHS]

20:52.583 --> 20:53.917
Have fun in LA, all right?

20:54.291 --> 20:55.291
Stay cool.

20:56.083 --> 20:57.458
I'll do my best.

20:57.458 --> 20:59.084
Shouldn't be too difficult. Heh.

20:59.792 --> 21:00.583
Why? 'Cause I was never

21:00.583 --> 21:01.667
really cool to begin with?

21:03.000 --> 21:04.000
You said it, not me.

21:04.000 --> 21:06.041
Ha ha ha.

21:06.041 --> 21:07.375
All right. I'll see you guys.

21:07.875 --> 21:10.084
- See ya. - Bye.

21:11.583 --> 21:13.917
Well, I guess geography is
destiny, huh?

21:14.333 --> 21:16.125
Here you are, stuck with me at
the end

21:16.125 --> 21:17.083
of your very last night in
Capeside.

21:17.083 --> 21:19.209
I wouldn't say "stuck" at all.
I think...

21:20.250 --> 21:21.750
I think this whole next-door
neighbor thing

21:21.750 --> 21:22.750
worked out for the best.

21:23.291 --> 21:24.834
Yeah? How so?

21:25.708 --> 21:27.167
Joey and Pacey and I grew up in

21:27.167 --> 21:28.417
mortal terror of this house,

21:29.084 --> 21:30.583
especially around Halloween.

21:30.583 --> 21:32.167
Every time Grams came out to
sweep her porch,

21:32.167 --> 21:33.167
I think we half-expected her

21:33.167 --> 21:34.084
to hop on her broomstick

21:34.084 --> 21:34.959
and fly away.

21:34.959 --> 21:36.125
Ha ha. Sounds like her.

21:36.125 --> 21:37.291
Ha ha.

21:37.291 --> 21:39.750
Pacey once offered Joey I think
a whole dollar

21:39.750 --> 21:41.291
just to run up and touch the
front door.

21:41.291 --> 21:42.834
Ha ha. Did she do it?

21:42.834 --> 21:43.834
No, are you kidding?

21:43.834 --> 21:45.291
She's still afraid of your
grandmother.

21:47.583 --> 21:48.959
I guess that makes me the Boo
Radley

21:48.959 --> 21:50.083
of this scenario, huh?

21:50.083 --> 21:53.417
Exactly. Except beautiful and
with breasts.

21:55.458 --> 21:57.125
Wit. We like that around here.

21:58.458 --> 22:00.458
[SIGHS]

22:01.083 --> 22:02.875
[SIGHS]

22:02.875 --> 22:04.209
Come here.

22:07.583 --> 22:08.667
Jen: Mm.

22:10.208 --> 22:11.375
Ok.

22:12.000 --> 22:12.625
Go.

22:12.625 --> 22:13.875
Get the hell out of here.

22:14.125 --> 22:14.959
Walk across that lawn,

22:14.959 --> 22:16.000
have a great life,

22:16.000 --> 22:17.000
and don't ever call me again.

22:17.000 --> 22:18.375
What? So I can confirm your

22:18.375 --> 22:19.583
worst fears about men?

22:19.583 --> 22:21.000
Yes, exactly.

22:21.041 --> 22:23.667
Oh, wait, I forgot. We never
slept together.

22:24.000 --> 22:25.375
You got five minutes?

22:27.000 --> 22:28.333
For you? Always.

22:32.834 --> 22:33.834
[DOOR OPENS]

22:34.417 --> 22:36.333
I'm sorry. I... I didn't mean
to interrupt.

22:36.333 --> 22:37.375
Uh...

22:37.375 --> 22:39.500
Uh, Grams, it's fine. It...
it...

22:41.417 --> 22:42.917
I think we're all done here?

22:43.667 --> 22:45.792
Doomed to be friends forever.

22:48.500 --> 22:49.667
Mm.

22:51.500 --> 22:52.667
Sucks, doesn't it?

23:19.291 --> 23:21.166
Not the most practical choice,
mind you,

23:21.166 --> 23:22.500
but I gotta admit,

23:23.083 --> 23:24.458
it sure as hell looks cool.

23:27.959 --> 23:29.041
Cooler than the t21?

23:29.041 --> 23:32.750
Hardly. But, hey, to each his
own.

23:36.917 --> 23:38.000
You know, it's funny.

23:39.583 --> 23:41.542
I knew I'd be sad to see you go.

23:42.458 --> 23:44.125
What I didn't expect was this
feeling

23:45.000 --> 23:46.458
of not wanting you to go.

23:48.667 --> 23:50.208
Son or not, Dawson...

23:51.792 --> 23:53.458
You are one of my favorite
people.

24:04.042 --> 24:05.917
Ok. All right. Ahem. Let me see.

24:05.917 --> 24:07.583
Have I covered everything? Um...

24:08.209 --> 24:10.209
You know not to have sex
without a condom, right?

24:10.209 --> 24:10.917
Aw, dad, please. I was the

24:10.917 --> 24:11.708
only kid in kindergarten

24:11.708 --> 24:13.000
who knew what Trojans were.

24:13.000 --> 24:14.917
Right. Um... drugs.

24:14.917 --> 24:16.458
I can't swear to you that I'll
never

24:16.458 --> 24:19.042
try some variety of narcotic,

24:19.042 --> 24:21.250
but I can promise you

24:21.250 --> 24:23.291
I'll never get so strung out I
steal your TV.

24:23.583 --> 24:24.583
Can you promise me...

24:25.041 --> 24:26.375
You won't join a frat.

24:27.125 --> 24:27.792
That I can promise.

24:27.792 --> 24:28.792
Dad: Ok.

24:34.167 --> 24:35.834
So tell me what it was like...

24:36.959 --> 24:38.042
Saying good-bye to Joey.

24:39.167 --> 24:40.209
[SIGHS]

24:40.209 --> 24:41.333
It was, um...

24:43.084 --> 24:44.291
It was like most other things
in life

24:44.291 --> 24:46.167
you have too many expectations
of.

24:47.291 --> 24:50.583
You know? Totally, completely
underwhelming.

24:52.084 --> 24:53.166
Well, I will tell you this...

24:54.208 --> 24:57.542
And it is the last piece of
fatherly advice

24:57.542 --> 24:59.167
I dispense before you leave the
nest.

25:00.500 --> 25:01.542
It ain't over...

25:02.667 --> 25:03.667
'Till it's over.

25:05.917 --> 25:07.875
That's it? That's your advice,

25:07.875 --> 25:09.166
a trite, hackneyed cliché?

25:09.458 --> 25:11.000
It was all I could think of.

25:12.125 --> 25:13.125
Major demerits, dad.

25:16.625 --> 25:17.708
[SIGHS]

25:19.834 --> 25:21.375
You know, when I first got here,

25:21.375 --> 25:22.792
I thought that I was being
punished.

25:22.792 --> 25:25.000
That... that my mom sent me away

25:25.000 --> 25:25.917
'cause she just didn't love

25:25.917 --> 25:26.917
me enough or something.

25:27.333 --> 25:28.125
Jennifer.

25:28.125 --> 25:29.542
But I don't think so now.

25:29.834 --> 25:32.042
I mean, I think that she really
loved it here.

25:33.209 --> 25:34.917
This house, the creek, I...

25:35.917 --> 25:37.750
I mean, she was always looking
for an excuse

25:37.750 --> 25:39.458
to bring me here... Christmas

25:39.458 --> 25:41.167
or vacation, anything.

25:41.167 --> 25:42.167
Hmm.

25:42.167 --> 25:44.042
Those were good times...

25:45.042 --> 25:46.750
But sad for her.

25:48.625 --> 25:49.625
Why's that?

25:50.167 --> 25:52.500
Some people spend their entire
lives

25:52.500 --> 25:54.834
chasing the happiness they had
in high school...

25:55.875 --> 25:57.042
Their teenage years.

25:58.000 --> 26:00.125
Thank goodness that won't
happen to you.

26:00.917 --> 26:01.917
Why do you say that?

26:01.917 --> 26:04.083
You children, the way you carry
on,

26:04.083 --> 26:06.875
always so dour and depressed
about everything.

26:06.875 --> 26:08.291
Things can only get better from
here.

26:09.333 --> 26:10.959
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

26:11.875 --> 26:14.125
Heavens, who could that be at
this hour?

26:16.084 --> 26:17.125
I know. I got halfway home

26:17.125 --> 26:18.417
and then I decided I didn't
like the thought

26:18.417 --> 26:19.417
of you two all alone

26:19.417 --> 26:21.708
in this house on your last
night.

26:21.708 --> 26:23.959
[LAUGHS] Another sentimentalist.

26:24.667 --> 26:26.458
Now, as long as you're here...

26:26.458 --> 26:28.750
Yes. I thought you packed
everything.

26:28.750 --> 26:30.708
Oh, I still have a few tricks
up my sleeve.

26:31.542 --> 26:34.500
So... you're really not sad to
be leaving?

26:36.209 --> 26:37.458
Not sad.

26:38.458 --> 26:42.000
Actually, it's rather
exhilarating,

26:42.000 --> 26:44.167
leaving all this behind.

26:45.542 --> 26:47.583
You know, we three are about to

26:47.583 --> 26:49.583
embark on a great adventure.

26:52.917 --> 26:54.834
Did you and Gramps always live
here?

26:54.834 --> 26:57.167
No. When your grandfather and I
were married

26:57.167 --> 26:58.083
he was still in law school,

26:58.083 --> 27:00.209
so we lived with his parents
for a while.

27:01.000 --> 27:03.083
I would not recommend that.

27:05.834 --> 27:09.209
Then we moved downtown above
his law office.

27:09.375 --> 27:10.708
Oh, I didn't know that.

27:10.708 --> 27:13.458
Huh. That apartment.

27:15.042 --> 27:17.542
In the summer it was so hot.

27:19.209 --> 27:20.417
Summer nights, we'd take a

27:20.417 --> 27:21.792
blanket up on the roof.

27:23.375 --> 27:24.166
Under the stars.

27:24.166 --> 27:25.166
Mm.

27:26.417 --> 27:29.834
Stars and the lights from the
summer houses.

27:31.041 --> 27:33.125
Saturday nights, the owners
would

27:33.125 --> 27:35.542
string Japanese lanterns along
the docks

27:36.167 --> 27:37.834
and have these very fancy

27:37.834 --> 27:39.834
dinner dances on the lawn.

27:41.166 --> 27:44.208
Nat King Cole, Frank Sinatra

27:45.167 --> 27:47.000
drifting across the water.

27:47.000 --> 27:48.500
Ohh, that sounds magical.

27:49.042 --> 27:50.583
Oh, it was.

27:52.000 --> 27:53.542
So your grandfather and I
decided

27:53.542 --> 27:55.583
the best way for us to be happy

27:55.875 --> 27:57.542
would be to buy one of those
summer houses

27:57.542 --> 27:59.625
and live in it all year-round.

28:02.417 --> 28:05.000
And it worked, right? You guys
were happy here.

28:07.000 --> 28:08.458
We certainly were...

28:12.209 --> 28:14.333
But we were always cold in the
winter.

28:18.542 --> 28:20.209
[PHONE RINGS]

28:21.209 --> 28:22.000
Hello.

28:22.417 --> 28:23.959
Pacey [ON PHONE]: Dawson, is
that you?

28:23.959 --> 28:24.959
Pacey?

28:24.959 --> 28:26.625
Yeah, man. I hope it's not too
late.

28:26.625 --> 28:27.875
N-no, it's fine. It's...

28:27.875 --> 28:29.291
Uh, where are you?

28:29.291 --> 28:32.125
Heh heh, I'm in paradise, man,
paradise.

28:32.667 --> 28:33.959
Heh heh.

28:33.959 --> 28:35.291
Hey, you laugh, but it's true.

28:36.959 --> 28:39.125
So, uh, how's everything goin'?

28:39.125 --> 28:41.042
Heh heh, I tell you,

28:41.042 --> 28:42.458
it has been the hardest work I
have ever done

28:42.458 --> 28:43.458
in my entire life,

28:44.167 --> 28:45.291
but, well, it's probably a good
thing.

28:45.291 --> 28:46.667
It keeps my mind off of stuff.

28:47.834 --> 28:48.917
Hmm.

28:50.792 --> 28:51.792
So how is she?

28:52.125 --> 28:53.125
She's, um...

28:53.834 --> 28:54.792
You know, she's doing the

28:54.792 --> 28:55.834
same thing you are, Pace.

28:55.834 --> 28:56.917
She's keepin' busy.

28:57.291 --> 28:59.084
[SIGHS]

28:59.084 --> 29:00.542
She doesn't say much, but, um...

29:01.458 --> 29:02.291
You know, I get the feeling

29:02.291 --> 29:03.166
that she thinks about you

29:03.166 --> 29:05.125
every 10 seconds or so.

29:06.667 --> 29:08.125
I know she'd appreciate a call.

29:11.291 --> 29:12.875
Uh, you know, I just don't think

29:12.875 --> 29:15.084
that's a place I'm ready to go
quite yet, Dawson.

29:15.084 --> 29:16.458
Yeah, I totally understand.

29:17.542 --> 29:19.083
I could say something to her if
you want.

29:19.500 --> 29:21.166
No. No, you know what?

29:21.166 --> 29:22.417
I think I'd prefer if you
didn't,

29:22.417 --> 29:23.542
and that's...

29:24.209 --> 29:25.667
that's not why I called,
actually.

29:25.667 --> 29:26.834
Pacey: Uh...

29:29.542 --> 29:31.209
I just... I realized that you're

29:31.209 --> 29:32.583
the only person in Capeside

29:32.583 --> 29:34.542
that I actually regret not
saying good-bye to,

29:34.875 --> 29:37.209
because, you know, for a long
time there, Dawson,

29:37.750 --> 29:39.125
being your best friend

29:39.125 --> 29:40.667
was all I really cared about in
my life.

29:43.667 --> 29:45.125
I just wanted you to hear from
me

29:45.125 --> 29:45.959
that despite everything

29:45.959 --> 29:47.000
that's happened between us

29:47.000 --> 29:49.542
and the miles that may be
between us right now,

29:49.542 --> 29:50.542
you know, I still think

29:50.542 --> 29:51.792
about the way things were.

29:54.458 --> 29:56.042
Back when we were just a couple
dorks

29:56.042 --> 29:57.209
wondering if and when a girl

29:57.209 --> 29:58.000
would ever look our way?

29:59.291 --> 30:01.458
Heh heh, well, speak for
yourself, huh?

30:01.458 --> 30:03.084
[LAUGHS]

30:04.250 --> 30:07.000
Yeah, Pace, I'm... I'm really
glad you called,

30:07.000 --> 30:09.125
because the worst thing about
not saying good-bye

30:09.125 --> 30:10.375
was I didn't get a chance to
tell you

30:10.375 --> 30:12.167
something I wanted so badly to
tell you.

30:12.583 --> 30:13.834
What's that?

30:16.125 --> 30:17.708
I'm proud of you, Pacey.

30:21.583 --> 30:22.583
Thanks, Dawson.

30:26.750 --> 30:27.959
Good luck out there.

30:29.208 --> 30:30.208
Yeah.

30:30.708 --> 30:31.708
You, too.

30:58.583 --> 31:00.208
[SIGHS]

31:11.708 --> 31:12.708
Hey.

31:13.583 --> 31:15.000
Heh. Hey.

31:16.208 --> 31:17.208
What are you doing here?

31:19.000 --> 31:20.000
Well...

31:20.667 --> 31:22.167
I thought if I don't help you
pack, Dawson,

31:22.167 --> 31:24.084
Uh, you're gonna end up in LA.

31:24.084 --> 31:25.333
With just those clothes on your
back,

31:25.333 --> 31:27.208
and chances are that after a
while

31:27.208 --> 31:29.167
they're gonna start to smell a
little,

31:29.167 --> 31:30.291
and that's no way to make

31:30.291 --> 31:31.667
a good first impression.

31:32.333 --> 31:34.125
My hygiene thanks you for your
concern.

31:34.125 --> 31:35.167
Sure.

31:36.583 --> 31:38.125
So where are you headed off to?

31:39.083 --> 31:40.291
The Potter B&amp;B.

31:41.458 --> 31:43.166
What was your excuse gonna be?

31:43.166 --> 31:44.167
I was gonna work the whole.

31:44.167 --> 31:44.959
"I haven't said good-bye

31:44.959 --> 31:46.209
"to Bessie or Bodie yet" angle.

31:46.209 --> 31:48.500
Ah. Not bad.

31:48.500 --> 31:49.667
Heh, come on.

31:54.917 --> 31:58.959
♪ [END CREDITS OF A MOVIE MUSIC
PLAY] ♪

32:02.167 --> 32:03.125
I caught that.

32:05.875 --> 32:06.875
Sue me.

32:08.041 --> 32:09.041
It's still my favorite movie.

32:09.041 --> 32:10.250
This won the Oscar, right?

32:10.250 --> 32:12.209
God, how many times do I have
to tell you?

32:12.209 --> 32:13.083
It was Gandhi.

32:13.917 --> 32:15.375
- Right. - [SIGHS]

32:23.667 --> 32:25.125
I need your help here.

32:25.917 --> 32:27.125
[SIGHS] I've said it before,

32:27.125 --> 32:28.167
and I'll say it again.

32:28.417 --> 32:29.708
[ZIP]

32:29.708 --> 32:31.208
You're worse than a girl,
Dawson Leery.

32:31.208 --> 32:32.750
That's good. Emasculate me.

32:32.750 --> 32:34.667
It's only the last time you're
ever gonna see me.

32:35.167 --> 32:36.667
Well, for Christmas, I suppose.

32:36.667 --> 32:39.167
Which is six months away, whole
lifetime.

32:39.167 --> 32:40.208
You know by then you'll be
married

32:40.208 --> 32:42.375
to the first bimbo who slips
you her head shot.

32:42.375 --> 32:43.000
[ZIP]

32:43.000 --> 32:44.750
And you'll be shacked up with
the first guy

32:44.750 --> 32:46.166
who offers you a hit off his
beer bong.

32:46.417 --> 32:48.125
Right.

32:49.125 --> 32:52.458
I wish we could just fast
forward four years,

32:52.458 --> 32:54.708
and see how it all ends up.

32:55.125 --> 32:56.750
I don't have to, really. I
mean...

32:57.417 --> 32:58.834
Four years at Worthington,
you'll

32:58.834 --> 33:00.000
be a pedigreed professional.

33:00.125 --> 33:01.250
And you?

33:01.250 --> 33:02.834
I'll be working the graveyard

33:02.834 --> 33:04.167
shift over at Kinko's.

33:04.167 --> 33:05.542
Stop by and say hi.

33:05.542 --> 33:06.542
Mm-hmm.

33:07.125 --> 33:08.625
[SIGHS]

33:11.917 --> 33:12.917
Dawson...

33:12.917 --> 33:13.917
Yeah.

33:14.750 --> 33:16.542
I know we always joke about
this, but...

33:18.542 --> 33:20.458
I feel like I'm never gonna see
you again.

33:20.458 --> 33:21.917
That's crazy talk, Jo.

33:21.917 --> 33:23.375
I know. I...

33:23.375 --> 33:24.500
I know I'll see you again,

33:24.500 --> 33:26.667
and it probably won't be too
long from now,

33:26.667 --> 33:29.209
you know, holidays, most
likely, but...

33:31.625 --> 33:33.042
You'll be different.

33:34.000 --> 33:35.000
I will?

33:35.208 --> 33:36.458
Well, you'll have a tan.

33:38.209 --> 33:39.250
And you'll have a girlfriend.

33:39.250 --> 33:40.375
I will?

33:40.375 --> 33:42.000
She'll be incredibly pretty.

33:42.000 --> 33:42.875
Really?

33:42.875 --> 33:43.667
You'll show me a picture,

33:43.667 --> 33:44.583
I'll immediately hate her,

33:44.583 --> 33:46.166
and the worse part is, deep
down,

33:46.166 --> 33:48.083
I'll know she's as great as you
say she is

33:48.083 --> 33:49.667
because... you like her.

33:50.209 --> 33:51.792
You sound pretty sure about all
this.

33:51.792 --> 33:53.583
Well, you can't keep it a
secret forever, Dawson.

33:53.583 --> 33:54.667
What's that?

33:56.834 --> 33:58.042
How incredible you are.

34:03.291 --> 34:04.667
Ok, film student...

34:07.000 --> 34:08.542
All-time favorite movie.

34:08.542 --> 34:10.208
You want to play that game?

34:10.208 --> 34:10.208
You want to play that game?
Mm-hmm.

34:10.208 --> 34:11.208
Mm-hmm.

34:13.667 --> 34:14.667
Jaws.

34:15.125 --> 34:16.792
You, all-time favorite song.

34:16.792 --> 34:19.083
"Daydream Believer."  Most
embarrassing moment.

34:19.792 --> 34:21.000
Uh...

34:21.000 --> 34:22.625
That would have to be when the
whole school

34:22.625 --> 34:24.042
watched me make out with Eve.

34:24.042 --> 34:25.125
What are you talking about?

34:25.500 --> 34:27.417
That did wonders for your
street cred.

34:27.417 --> 34:28.417
[LAUGHS]

34:29.042 --> 34:30.083
Ok.

34:30.333 --> 34:31.333
You, same question.

34:32.333 --> 34:34.708
Hmm. That's easy. Right here in
this room

34:34.708 --> 34:36.083
when I offered to have sex with
you,

34:36.083 --> 34:37.000
and you turned me down cold.

34:37.958 --> 34:38.708
Y-y-y-yeah.

34:38.708 --> 34:40.083
Hey, could we introduce the
"hugest"

34:40.083 --> 34:41.042
"all-time regret" category,

34:41.042 --> 34:42.375
because that would pretty much
be mine.

34:44.291 --> 34:45.750
Mine would be...

34:47.333 --> 34:49.125
Lying to you about sleeping
with Pacey.

34:51.166 --> 34:52.166
[LAUGHS]

34:53.583 --> 34:54.542
That's not funny.

34:54.542 --> 34:56.291
Not, it's that... I just...

34:58.167 --> 35:01.500
I'm the only one who has not
had sex.

35:03.500 --> 35:07.166
I... I didn't plan on
graduating a virgin.

35:07.166 --> 35:09.125
What... what happened?

35:11.125 --> 35:12.209
Best laid plans...

35:12.209 --> 35:14.083
This mythical college
girlfriend I'm gonna have,

35:14.083 --> 35:15.166
will she have sex with me?

35:15.500 --> 35:18.083
Mm... no, sorry. She's a prude.

35:19.875 --> 35:21.125
Damn. I had such high hopes

35:21.125 --> 35:22.083
the last American virgin

35:22.083 --> 35:23.792
would fare better as an
undergrad.

35:29.208 --> 35:31.041
All-time most life altering
moment.

35:32.125 --> 35:32.750
Ever?

35:32.750 --> 35:33.750
Ever.

35:36.166 --> 35:37.250
Well...

35:39.667 --> 35:41.834
There are a lot of winners
there.

35:42.792 --> 35:44.333
[SIGHS]

35:48.458 --> 35:51.542
But, you know, there was this
one moment, um...

35:53.375 --> 35:54.959
A couple years ago...

35:55.959 --> 35:57.125
In this room. I was standing

35:57.125 --> 35:58.458
over there by the window,

35:58.959 --> 35:59.959
and, uh...

36:02.125 --> 36:03.333
And you kissed me.

36:06.792 --> 36:08.000
It changed everything.

36:11.875 --> 36:13.000
It's a pretty powerful thing

36:13.000 --> 36:14.209
when you get your biggest wish

36:14.209 --> 36:15.583
in one moment.

36:23.625 --> 36:25.041
Oh, better not forget that one.

36:25.041 --> 36:26.708
Gee, I almost forgot.

36:36.792 --> 36:37.834
Dawson...

36:42.125 --> 36:43.708
I want you to stay.

36:46.208 --> 36:47.208
Excuse me?

36:48.125 --> 36:49.083
I said, I want you to stay.

36:49.333 --> 36:51.208
And there, I said it.

36:53.000 --> 36:54.041
You don't think you could have
maybe

36:54.041 --> 36:55.417
said something before I packed?

36:55.417 --> 36:57.458
No, I said it, and now I want
you to forget it.

36:57.875 --> 36:58.875
Forget it?

36:59.083 --> 37:00.875
Jo, how do I forget that?

37:01.291 --> 37:02.250
Well, it's just something that

37:02.250 --> 37:03.083
I've been thinking about,

37:03.083 --> 37:04.291
and I wanted you to know

37:04.291 --> 37:05.917
that I was thinking about it.

37:06.667 --> 37:08.042
You know, I was just gonna...

37:08.291 --> 37:10.041
Keep my mouth shut and let you
go...

37:11.083 --> 37:12.291
But...[SIGHS]...

37:12.834 --> 37:15.042
It's not me. That's some
merchant ivory movie,

37:15.042 --> 37:17.084
you know, where people suffer
in silence,

37:17.084 --> 37:18.208
and you're supposed to be so
impressed

37:18.208 --> 37:19.667
by their restraint. Well...

37:21.000 --> 37:22.000
You know...

37:23.667 --> 37:25.042
Sorry, but screw that.

37:30.167 --> 37:31.375
My best friend in the whole
world

37:31.375 --> 37:32.583
is leaving tomorrow,

37:33.042 --> 37:34.708
and a big part of me wants him
to stay...

37:37.042 --> 37:39.667
So I hope you don't hate me.

37:42.792 --> 37:44.000
I could never hate you, Joey...

37:48.375 --> 37:50.166
And not for lack of trying,
either.

37:56.084 --> 37:57.166
These past couple of years,

37:57.166 --> 37:59.291
it's been one big soap opera.

38:00.917 --> 38:02.708
I wouldn't take it back. I
wouldn't...

38:03.209 --> 38:04.500
Take any of it back, but...

38:06.167 --> 38:07.250
I'm glad that it's over.

38:09.167 --> 38:10.708
'Cause I like the way things
are now.

38:13.250 --> 38:15.250
My life being the cruel joke
that it is,

38:15.959 --> 38:17.708
now that things are so nice...

38:19.625 --> 38:20.708
You're leaving.

38:28.208 --> 38:29.208
Jo...

38:33.667 --> 38:34.542
If I thought for one second

38:34.542 --> 38:36.166
it was the right thing to do,

38:37.208 --> 38:38.542
I would stay,

38:38.542 --> 38:40.042
but it's time to go.

38:42.834 --> 38:44.375
It's time for me to get out of
this room,

38:44.375 --> 38:45.375
and it's time for you

38:45.375 --> 38:48.542
to discover who you are without
us.

38:51.125 --> 38:53.209
This chapter's over, Jo.

38:56.041 --> 38:58.167
I can feel it.

39:03.792 --> 39:05.166
Do you believe in magic?

39:10.333 --> 39:12.834
I never used to. I mean, how
could I?

39:14.166 --> 39:16.084
13, your mom dies.

39:17.084 --> 39:19.792
You hope against hope for...
for magic,

39:19.792 --> 39:21.375
something to make it all better.

39:22.209 --> 39:23.250
It never comes,

39:23.250 --> 39:26.125
and, you know, you look to your
father

39:26.125 --> 39:30.000
who's unable to overcome all of
his tragic flaws.

39:30.000 --> 39:32.375
Well, no abracadabra there.

39:34.042 --> 39:35.375
And then there's Pacey. Well...

39:37.125 --> 39:38.667
Any magic that was there,

39:38.667 --> 39:40.291
that ran out, didn't it?

39:44.625 --> 39:46.166
But, uh, then there's you.

39:50.250 --> 39:52.041
There's proof that someone out
there

39:52.041 --> 39:53.959
is thinking of me...

39:56.708 --> 39:58.458
My friend who was with me
always.

40:03.917 --> 40:05.208
It's pure magic.

40:09.125 --> 40:10.583
I guess this is pretty much

40:10.583 --> 40:11.917
just a long-winded way

40:11.917 --> 40:13.583
of saying that, um...

40:15.083 --> 40:16.250
I'm gonna miss you, Dawson.

40:20.000 --> 40:22.125
I'm gonna miss you, too, Joey.

40:31.875 --> 40:33.250
Well, I guess it's getting late,

40:33.250 --> 40:35.000
and you need to rest, so...

40:36.333 --> 40:37.583
It kind of makes me wish that
the

40:37.583 --> 40:38.792
ladder was still out there...

40:40.500 --> 40:42.625
Make a classy exit, you know?

40:43.291 --> 40:45.542
Disappear out the window into
the night.

40:46.250 --> 40:47.250
Yeah.

40:48.209 --> 40:49.333
Far more cinematic.

40:58.083 --> 41:01.125
Wow. I guess this is, uh...

41:02.834 --> 41:04.125
This is really it, huh?

41:07.708 --> 41:08.917
See you, Dawson.

41:10.834 --> 41:12.000
I'll see you, Joey.

41:17.959 --> 41:19.625
So what was yours, by the way?

41:21.291 --> 41:22.291
What was my what?

41:27.167 --> 41:29.542
Your all-time most life
altering moment?

41:33.959 --> 41:36.209
For all I know, it could be
this one right now...

41:40.209 --> 41:41.291
Saying good-bye to you.

42:02.250 --> 42:06.208
